For years, HTTP API design has had an awkward gap.
GET has the right semantics for reading data, but complex search parameters do not fit comfortably in a URL. POST gives you a request body, but it does not tell clients, proxies, or infrastructure that the operation is safe to repeat.
RFC 10008 introduces a standard answer: the HTTP QUERY method.
QUERY lets a client send structured query input in the request body while explicitly declaring that the operation is safe and idempotent. The response is also cacheable under HTTP semantics.
For JavaScript developers, the interesting part is that the basic plumbing already works. Browsers and Node.js can send custom HTTP methods. The less convenient part is that routers, caches, CDNs, CORS configurations, and testing tools still need time to catch up.

Why GET and POST are both imperfect for complex reads
Imagine an article search endpoint with full-text search, multiple filters, sorting, and pagination.
A typical GET request might start like this:
const params = new URLSearchParams({
q: "distributed systems",
sort: "-published",
status: "active,draft",
tags: JSON.stringify(["node", "graphql"])
});const res = await fetch(`/api/articles?${params}`);
This works until it doesn’t. This is fine for small, flat inputs. Browsers, proxies, and CDNs disagree on how long a URL can be — usually somewhere around 2000–8000 characters, but never guaranteed.
There are also operational concerns:

• URLs pass through systems with different size limits.

• Complex values require encoding and are difficult to inspect.

• Request URLs commonly appear in access logs, analytics tools, browser history, and bookmarks.

• A large filter object encoded into a URL effectively creates a separate URI for every possible combination.
The usual workaround is a POST endpoint:
const response = await fetch("/api/articles/search", {
method: "POST",
headers: {
"Content-Type": "application/json"
},
body: JSON.stringify({
q: "distributed systems",
sort: "-publishedAt",
status: ["active", "draft"],
tags: ["node", "graphql"]
})
});This solves the serialization problem, but it loses useful protocol-level meaning. A generic HTTP client cannot tell whether this POST creates an article, charges a card, records an event, or merely searches a database.
Your application may know that the endpoint is read-only. The network does not.

What QUERY changes
A QUERY request looks similar to POST, but its semantics are different:
QUERY /api/articles HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json {
"q": "distributed systems",
"status": ["active", "draft"]
}
RFC 10008 defines QUERY as:

• safe — the client is not asking the target resource to change state;

• idempotent — repeating the same request has the same intended effect;

• cacheable — a cache may reuse a stored response for an equivalent QUERY request;

• body-aware — the request content and its Content-Type define the query.
That last point matters for caching. A cache key for QUERY cannot be based only on the URL. It also has to incorporate the request body and relevant metadata.
QUERY is therefore not “GET with a body.” It is a separate HTTP method with its own defined semantics.
Sending QUERY with fetch()
The Fetch API already accepts custom HTTP method tokens. QUERY is not one of the forbidden methods, so a same-origin request can be written normally:
const response = await fetch("/api/articles", {
method: "QUERY",
headers: {
"Content-Type": "application/json",
Accept: "application/json"
},
body: JSON.stringify({
q: "distributed systems",
limit: 10,
sort: "-publishedAt",
filters: {
status: ["active", "draft"],
tags: ["node", "graphql"]
}
})
}); if (!response.ok) {
throw new Error(`Search failed with ${response.status}`);
}
const result = await response.json();
This does not mean the entire browser ecosystem supports QUERY as a first-class method yet.
For a cross-origin request, QUERY is not a CORS-safelisted method, so the browser will send a preflight request. The server must explicitly allow it:
Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, QUERY, OPTIONSThe browser’s built-in HTTP cache also should not be assumed to cache QUERY responses today, even though the RFC permits it. Existing browser and intermediary implementations were largely designed around GET and HEAD cache keys.
A service worker can still intercept a QUERY request and return a custom response. However, the Cache API’s normal matching behavior is centered on GET and HEAD, so body-aware caching requires application code rather than wishful thinking.
Sending QUERY from Node.js
Node’s low-level HTTP client accepts a method as a string:
import { request } from "node:http"; function sendQuery(url, input) {
return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
const payload = JSON.stringify(input);
const target = new URL(url);
const req = request( {
protocol: target.protocol,
hostname: target.hostname,
port: target.port,
path: `${target.pathname}${target.search}`,
method: "QUERY",
headers: {
"Content-Type": "application/json",
Accept: "application/json",
"Content-Length": Buffer.byteLength(payload)
}
},
(res) => {
const chunks = [];
res.on("data", (chunk) => chunks.push(chunk));
res.on("end", () => {
const text = Buffer.concat(chunks).toString("utf8");
const contentType = res.headers["content-type"] ?? "";
resolve({
status: res.statusCode ?? 0,
headers: res.headers,
body: contentType.includes("application/json") ? JSON.parse(text) : text
});
});
}
);
req.on("error", reject); req.end(payload); }); }
const result = await sendQuery("http://localhost:3000/api/articles", {
q: "http query",
limit: 5
});
console.log(result.status, result.body);
For server-to-server communication, adoption is mostly under your control. You still need to verify that reverse proxies, API gateways, WAF rules, observability tools, and CDNs accept the method rather than rejecting or normalizing it.
Handling QUERY in Express
Express does not currently provide an app.query() route helper. The reliable option is app.all() and a method check:
import express from "express"; const app = express();
app.use(express.json({ limit: "100kb" }));
app.all("/api/articles", async (req, res, next) => {
if (req.method !== "QUERY") {
return next();
}
const {
q = "",
limit = 20,
sort = "-publishedAt",
filters = {}
} = req.body ?? {};
if (!Number.isInteger(limit) || limit < 1 || limit > 100) {
return res.status(400).json({ error: "limit must be an integer between 1 and 100" });
}
const result = await searchArticles({ q, limit, sort, filters });
res
.set("Accept-Query", "application/json")
.set("Cache-Control", "private, max-age=30")
.status(200)
.json(result);
});
The Accept-Query response header advertises the media types the resource accepts for QUERY requests. It is about query formats, not whether the method exists.
Support for the method itself can be advertised with Allow in an OPTIONS response:
app.options("/api/articles", (req, res) => {
res
.set("Allow", "GET, POST, QUERY, OPTIONS")
.set("Accept-Query", "application/json")
.status(204)
.end();
});Do not use app.on("query"): Express does not expose custom request methods as application events.
Detecting support
A client can inspect an endpoint’s OPTIONS response:
async function getQuerySupport(url) {
const response = await fetch(url, { method: "OPTIONS" });
const methods = (response.headers.get("Allow") ?? "")
.split(",")
.map((method) => method.trim().toUpperCase())
.filter(Boolean); const mediaTypes = (response.headers.get("Accept-Query") ?? "")
.split(",") .map((type) => type.trim())
.filter(Boolean);
return { supported: methods.includes("QUERY"), mediaTypes }; }
This is useful when you own both sides of the API. On the public web, OPTIONS responses are not always configured consistently, so failed discovery should not automatically be interpreted as proof that QUERY is unsupported.

A practical fallback strategy
During a gradual rollout, supporting both QUERY and a legacy POST search endpoint is reasonable:
async function queryFetch(url, payload, options = {}) {
const { signal, fallbackUrl = `${url}/search` } = options;
const init = {
headers: {
"Content-Type": "application/json",
Accept: "application/json"
},
body: JSON.stringify(payload), signal
}; const response = await fetch(url, { ...init, method: "QUERY" });
if (response.status !== 405 && response.status !== 501) {
return response;
}
return fetch(fallbackUrl, { ...init, method: "POST" }); }
There is one limitation: a proxy may block an unfamiliar method before returning a normal HTTP response. In that case, fetch() can reject with a network error, which is indistinguishable from many unrelated failures.
Automatically retrying every network error as POST can duplicate traffic, so capability discovery or configuration is safer than blind fallback.

Cancellation and retries
AbortController works with QUERY in the same way it works with other fetch requests:
let controller; searchInput.addEventListener( "input", debounce(async (event) => {
controller?.abort();
controller = new AbortController();
try {
const response = await queryFetch( "/api/articles", {
q: event.target.value, limit: 8
},
{ signal: controller.signal } );
if (!response.ok) {
throw new Error(`Search failed with ${response.status}`);
}
renderResults(await response.json());
} catch (error) {
if (error.name !== "AbortError") {
console.error(error);
}
}
}, 200)
);
Cancellation itself is not the main benefit of QUERY; you can cancel a POST request too.
The benefit is semantic: because QUERY is defined as safe and idempotent, clients and infrastructure may retry it without assuming they are repeating a mutation.
Safe does not mean “the server performs no work.” A server can still write logs, update metrics, populate caches, or create auxiliary resources. It means those side effects are not what the client requested, and repeating the request must preserve the method’s intended semantics.

Testing without imaginary Supertest APIs
Mainstream Supertest APIs do not currently expose a standard .query() request method. Rather than relying on optional chaining around methods that do not exist, test the real HTTP endpoint with Node’s client.

Where QUERY is a good fit
QUERY is most useful when all three conditions are true:

• The operation is genuinely read-only from the client’s perspective.

• The input is too large or structured for a comfortable query string.

• You benefit from explicit safe and idempotent semantics.
Strong candidates include:

• faceted and full-text search;

• bulk lookup by hundreds of identifiers;

• analytics queries with nested dimensions and filters;

• read-only GraphQL operations;

• database-style query APIs;

• internal service-to-service requests with structured query documents.
It is a weaker fit for ordinary resource retrieval. GET /articles/123 remains simpler, more widely supported, and naturally bookmarkable.
It is also not a way to disguise mutations. A request that creates an order, marks a notification as read, or increments a business counter should not become QUERY merely because the response contains data.
